Sketchgodd is an artist based in Lagos, Nigeria (born 1996, in Ibadan). He has been painting professionally since 2019 but the art of painting has always played a big role in his life. Not only does he work with acrylic paint on canvases but also creates his art on murals. His illustrations are mostly street art, abstract art and graffiti, which are inspired by life events, his love for cartoons and music. 
Sketchgodd has worked for many great clients such as Dababy, Davido, Mayorkun, Dremo ,Jonzing world (Dprince and Ruger) and many more.
He is currently looking at expanding his work internationally as some of his commissions are for clients within Europe and US.

Oluwaseun Solomon Akinlo (b.1993) in Lagos state, Nigeria and he hails from Ondo states. Studied Fine and Applied Arts at Ladoke Akintola University of Technology, Ogbomoso, Oyo state. As an experimental artist, Oluwaseun has developed a passion for abstract expressionism and figurative art. His oeuvre encompasses paintings, vitrines and an array of works on canvas such as drawings, acrylic, collages, and altered photographs. Born out of investigative research and communication he conducts within his community, the end result is an emotional culmination of how their stories project on the emotional stayer of his mind shared as he listens to their voices

Oluwaseun’s expressionist style is a visual representation of
the human psyche, memories and emotions through a personal perspective on social, political, and cultural challenges, which confront the viewers with his evocative figures and use of colours. He was influenced by the community of Ajegunle where he grew up and influenced by their social, and cultural lifestyle.

Akinlo had exhibited in several exhibitions and Residency, ‘Our Time In The Sun’ Soto Art Gallery Lagos, Nigeria (2023),‘The Kids Are Not Alright’ AMG Project Art Gallery (2022- 2023), Mirrors of Emotions Art Exhibition at Pop-central TV Lagos (2022), 1952Africa Art Residency(2022), TABFamily Exhibition at CoolChange Contemporary Art in Australia (2022), 2nd Experience at The Kokopelli Gallery (2021), Resilience Art Exhibition at National Gallery Enugu (2019), ‘Twilight’ Life In My City Fest at Thought Pyramid Gallery Lagos (2018).

Ezekiel “Kiel” Orji, emerging from Lagos, is a artist specializing in Digital Art, Murals, and Merch Design. Melding Afro-futurism with advanced design, Kiel crafts an immersive digital experience that seamlessly transitions to tangible real-world installations. With nearly a decade of honed craftsmanship, he masterfully creates visual wonders while ingeniously monetizing them. His artistic realm, infused with avant-garde fashion, AI, AR, and Web3, weaves a contemporary tapestry where art and revolutionary digital commerce intertwine, offering a captivating panorama to the global stage.

Born in Lagos, Nigeria in the year 2000 but spent a chunk of my childhood in Port-Harcourt, Rivers state then a bit in Aba, Abia state with my secondary school situated in Calabar, Cross rivers state and tertiary institution, where I’m a computer science major, in Omu, Ogun state. I am a Lagos/Ogun state based self taught artist who’s art has one underlying theme regardless of medium, concept or technique; exploration. Drawing inspiration from his interaction with others, my environment and myself, I create art pieces that are not only visually striking, but self reflecting, with the hope that by striving to explore, understand, love and be true to myself, I’ll inspire my viewers to do the same. I’m versatile with several mediums including but not limited to oil-paints, charcoal/graphite, pastels and ballpoint pens. Since I decided to actively pursue a career in visual arts in 2021, I’ve partnered with a couple of NGO’s to conduct workshops with the sole aim of encouraging and inspiring creativity in young children and have taken part in two exhibitions, one being the Eco bank photography and art exhibition in 2022 And the second, “Outset” an exhibition organized by The Holy art gallery, London in April of 2023.  I recently took part in a portfolio review hosted by Tiwani contemporary where I met Andrew Pierre Hart, an internationally acclaimed artist, and it was a truly enlightening experience. I am currently an in house artist with Fobally art world Africa.

My Name is Abba Udeme, popularly known as Mentor's Art,I am an Artist from Akwa Ibom, south east of Nigeria. Throughout my life, I had always been fascinated by images and how the world is represented through the eyes of others. Reproducing what I sees on the paper started from my teenage years.This made me to surrounded myself with Artist of various areas of specialization ranging from pencils to acrylic. Artists such as Arinze Stanley has always been an inspiration to me with his hyperrealism drawing of charcoal artworks.  I, Abba Udeme, also known as Mentor's Art, was born in Akwa Ibom, grew up in Oyo State, Nigeria. I graduated as a Science Student of Polytechnic High School, Ijokodo, Ibadan. I later gained Admission into University of Ibadan, Ibadan Nigeria, to study Health Education.  Despite, my Course of studied, my passion  and aspirations of becoming a well known Artist grew stronger and stronger everyday and this had made me to developed my artistics skills more on variety of Mediums such as on paper, wall etc.  I love experimenting and creating beautiful artworks on papers and others mediums focusing on hyperealistics drawing of subject matter. Portrait drawing  is one of my favourite part of my art work because the subject can easily be recoghized if it is well drawn. I love expressing myself through my artwork because this is my medium of communication and it is my voice.

bio: Adeyewa is a modern-day artist from Nigeria whose artistic journey commenced in 2015. With seven years of painting experience under his belt, he possesses profound expertise and a wealth of knowledge in crafting exceptional artworks. Employing a mixed media technique, he skillfully produces cultural and traditional art pieces.   Adeyewa's aspiration lies in bridging the gap between African culture and the global community through his imaginative creations, which vividly portray the splendor and significance of African cultural heritage and principles. His works weave together themes of love, family, unity, and celebration through the use of figures and abstract which gives his art unparalleled beauty and intrinsic value.

bio: Benedict Akhere Kakulu, Specializing in painting, drawing, and scribbles, Benedict’s work is inspired by traditional African masks and sculptures. He began his artistic journey at age 7, pursued formal training at Rich Arts Studio, and completed an internship with Mr. Raji Babatunde at Space 29.7 Studios. A recent graduate from the University of Benin with a major in painting, he is also a fellow of the Museum of West African Art (MOWAA) in their UNEARTH archaeological program, dedicated to exploring and preserving indigenous heritage.

Born with an innate gift for expression, her artistic odyssey began as a young girl, sketching doodles on the margins of her school books. Miracle Ome, is a self-taught artist whose journey through creativity has been nothing short of obvious growth, which led to the discovery of her unique style of art called "Juxtapoism" which is a mix of traditional art, surrealism, mixed media and technology. For over a decade, she has been passionately honing her craft, leaving an indelible mark on the art world that captivates and enthralls viewers and critics alike.
